Generally, failing to parse expressions at the level of abstraction of the source code being debugged: I find it fails on user defined operators, can&#x27;t resolve overloaded functions, etc.<p>Even being able to reliably evaluate C++ expressions is far from what I want: I want to be able to execute arbitrary C++ statements (including loops), use templated objects that weren&#x27;t instantiated at compile time, etc.  I feel like this might be close to possible using, say, the LLVM JIT, although I haven&#x27;t seen anything that implies anyone is trying to build it.<p>edit: for example (stock gcc/gdb on Ubuntu 12.04):<p><pre><code>    #include <iostream>
    int main() { std::cout << &quot;foo\n&quot;; }
</code></pre>
in gdb, break at main:<p><pre><code>    (gdb) p std::cout << &quot;foo\n&quot;
    Cannot resolve function operator<< to any overloaded instance
</code></pre>
edit edit:  lldb doesn&#x27;t fare much better (OSX 10.9):<p><pre><code>    (lldb) p std::cout << &quot;foo\n&quot;
    error: no member named &#x27;cout&#x27; in namespace &#x27;std&#x27;
    error: 1 errors parsing expression</code></pre>
